text: No strategically calculated string high notes, no carefully placed "Inception Beats", no mass-pleasing jump scares. This trailer showed me a glimpse of hope, that in this grim darkness where almost everything are created in some corporate laboratory, there still are people like Ari Aster, who posses creativity & originality, as well as the means to execute them profoundly. Also let's be grateful to studios like A24, who are willing to take risks, who are backing their creative minds, who prioritize artistry over market research spreadsheets.   At least in 2019, some of us can still have nice things, Thank you very much A24, thank you!

text: This stuff is actually real. It happens now and has been going on for thousands of years. Cults not only exist, but are actually deeply integrated into the power structure of the world - in the west, north Africa, the middle east, central asia, india (of course), East asia and south east asia. Most people don't believe it simply because they're idiotically more impressed by gizmos like computers and not how the 50 trillion or so cells of their body and are able to make you. The "spirits" demand these sorts of rituals. Said otherwise: the insane dissociative identity disorders of the people who subscribe to this insane garbage believe that their power - over society, in particular - depends on their continued performance of these profoundly asymmetrical acts. That a movie can be made about it - like wickerman - evidently shows that the truth can be represented without many people much suspecting that these things happen all the time - and not at intervals of 90 years either. It's a yearly thing; and for some people, a daily thing.

text: The one visual I can't stop thinking about is her kneeling over and screaming in agony while the cult members surround her and mimic her.   I almost drowned when I was younger. While swimming at a friend's house in my neighborhood, I did a cannonball into the water. As I was coming up for air my friend jumped into the water and pulled me back under with him. I panicked and luckily I was tall enough to reach the bottom and push myself back up toward the surface, but I was a bit too late. While coming up I had to breathe and I inhaled a full breath of water. I remember my lungs locking up and I climbed out of the water and put my hands around my neck to show the other neighborhood kids I was choking. I couldn't speak. I couldn't breathe. It was terrifying. Instead of helping me they all started laughing and mimicking the same choking motion, even making the choking noises I was making.  Eventually, my lungs expelled the water, but damn, I'll never forget it.

text: As a swede I can tell you, we don‚Äôt really celebrate like this. Especially not in today‚Äôs day and age. Lol  We do drink A LOT though  I rewatched this again, and I can say with quite a bit of confidence that a lot of this isn‚Äôt quite right. A fair bit of the imagery is okay,  but I am very sceptical and feel sort of icky about the whole thing. Might be because they are taking the concept of a significant part of my culture and heritage and capitalising on it making it a horror movie. A gory one at that. Sure, I know Swedes and Scandis are involved, but still. I don‚Äôt like it. I don‚Äôt know. I mean sure, midsommar is an old  holiday. I assume it would be considered pagan. But still. It traditionally celebrates the summer solstice and everything coming back to life after the winter. I am pretty sure this is kind of how people of non western decent feel when their traditional jewellery and clothing is copied cheaply and worn as a costume, or when parts of their traditions and religion becomes a trendy fashion or fun past time. (Swedes have never been oppressed in the same way as certain other groups, and I understand  things like that might bear more significance than, but I feel like I can understand and with this relate on a very basic level) It‚Äôs not great. Also, Sweden is way more diverse than they‚Äôre making it look.

text: Dude the cinematography is fucking INSANE! In a way, it had a similar effect on me as the original Suspiria did due to the way images and lighting and colors are used to help build this insane atmosphere...the color scheme, the setting and the lighting...and just the imagery in general..has a HUGE impact on the film..  If you haven't seen this yet, please DO. If you loved hereditary, you will love this, too! It is a different story in a different setting but you can definitely tell they are from the same creator...I honestly have never been so on edge for almost an entire movie before...as soon as they arrive at their destination, I just had this like...pit in my stomach and I was so anxious...and it teases you for a little while, and relies on subtle little things and minor bizarre behavior to peak your interest...it's like...you know something terrible is coming but you just don't know what or how or why. Honestly the extended period of time building the atmosphere....patiently and intelligently....it makes it soooo much more effective when they FINALLY drop the axe and shit goes crazy... Just like cruising along at about 50 mph and then WAM! We at 100mph real fucking quick lmao. This may be divisive- some may not like it...but if hereditary is your ish, you are gonna LOVE this.

text: My quick honest no spoiler review: It's not a typical horror movie, and I understand why some may not like it. You can tell early on this is more of an attempt at art than trying to score cheap thrills. Is it "scary" in the traditional sense? No. But its not meant to terrify you with jump scares and such. It's smarter than that. It will likely continue processing in your brain well after you leave the theater. Cinematography and visuals is fantastic. The acting isn't Oscar-worthy, but more than acceptable. There are some gruesome scenes that are tough to watch and a few others that are sick and twisted with dark humor sprinkled in. It's an intense movie but its not like a fast roller coaster ride. This movie is a slow burn. It is long. Is it worth going to see? Yes I think so. If you are into this type of modern horror or into cult-based horror (ie: The Wicker Man), you'll probably like it. My score would be 8/10.

text: I'm baffled by how this can be labelled a horror film. Seeing the critics and viewing reviews scoring over 90% on rotten tomatoes and being a massive horror fan I couldn't wait to go and see this. After 2hours and God knows how many minutes I felt like I had been robbed of the ¬£11 I paid to watch it. At no point whatsoever did I feel on edge, uneasy, tense, scared, jumpy, unsettled or any other sense that I would associate with a "horror" film. If some one had said go see midsommar, it's a Swedish greatest showman on mushrooms then I would have had nothing but praise for this completely mind boggling musical with occasional deaths that seem utterly pointless. It's a shame because the quality of writing for what it actually is, the way in which it's been filmed, and some of the comedy in the film really are quite brilliant. Unfortunately it's not what it's been advertised as, a horror movie from the creator of hereditary

text: I've never been scared or affected by Gore movies/scenes but this was so much different. It took a huge affect on me. I then got a panic attack and almost had to walk out but I didn't want a beautiful/incredible/disturbing movie to make me walk out... So I decided to sit there with my eyes close when they showed the shape of a hollow face.I haven't had a bad panic attack for two years. this movie definitely has disturbed me. The lesson is don't watch this movie expecting so many horror elements because there's not much of that here. I might even say it's more of a slow burning psychological thriller. I personally enjoyed it because of it's different take on the genre and how it slowly cuts into your mind. I'm not saying it's wrong to hate it, I'm saying don't go to this movie with false expectations because that's the real problem here.

text: This movie had some good points, the cinematography was awesome and so was the music, the music really worked well. There is lots of really cool imagery used.   Beyond that, the movie is a 2.5 hour snorefest. Everything you expect to happen does, this is the definition of "been-there-done-that." Kill List did everything this film does, only 8 years earlier and 100x better. You can see the ending from a mile away about 15 minutes into the movie, unfortunately there is no twist. If you are new to "horror" flicks (horror in quotes because this film isnt really a horror flick at all, its a drama with some violent scenes) then this film may do it for you. Personally I felt like some of the horror fx were really poorly executed.   The setting is really interesting and unique, but I think ultimately it ended up taking away from the film. The characters are soooooooooo cliche and make some incredibly bone headed moves.   Its really a shame because I was looking forward to this film so much. I really wanted to like it but alas it fell very flat for me.

text: One of the most incredible moments I've ever had in a cinema in my entire life. This movie is truly a masterpiece. Everything works in synchrony for the mood of the movie: the lightning, the camera angles, the story pace, the sounds AND especially the silences. Again, Ari Aster and his crew delivers us a complex and intriguing experience. In my opinion this is not a horror movie. It's a "ritual" movie, if I should say so. A story about feelings everyone will face once or twice in a lifetime, about experiences that could destroy us or strengthen us.   If you enjoy works from Alejandro Jodorowsky, David Lynch and Roman Polanski. If you enjoy movies like Rosemary's Baby, The Shining, Janghwa Hongryeon. Games like the first three Silent Hill. Books from Neil Gaiman, Edgar Allan Poe. Believe me, you should see it. Also, if you're into this "Viking" series stuff or like things relationed to pagan rituals, you may also enjoy it.

text: This folk festivity, Midsommar, also exists in Romania, under the name of ''Sanziene'' (beautiful gentle fairies), celebrated on 24th of June, at the same time with the summer solstice. It is the strongest night for magic spells, especially for the love spells. Girls make crowns out of flowers and place flowers under the pillow at night to dream of their future husband. I connect really well with the movie, as it' my favorite folk tradition and we, Romanians share this with Sweden <3

Human beings have been ritualized-kill-crazy for thousands of years, executing literally millions of people because of their delusional/tribal beliefs. We even brought God into our madness with his participation in the ritualized torturing and killing of Jesus, as told in the old Bible fable. So now we have god sacrificing a god/human to himself before he can forgive us for our mistakes? Absolutely insane. You could show this film in any anthropology class as an example of a primitive human tribe doing all this deranged sh*t and it would fit right in with much of what actually happened in various cultures in our history! LOL.

text: Ari Aster is an ABSOLUTE mastermind. This movie surprisingly terrified me more than Hereditary did, and here's why (without spoilers).  If you haven't watched this film yet, be warned. Ari Aster is a master of sound manipulation and directorial shots in a mad scientist way of literally putting you INTO the fear of his films.  It's not what you're watching that's scary, it's what you're feeling that's scary, and that's something that I've never seen done in a horror film before.  If something bad has happened (or is going to happen), then you only have one of two directions to go because you're not going anywhere.   1. You'll understand what's happening while the actor does. Your heart will race because even if you knew what was about to happen, you're now trapped in it,  you can't stop it, and you can't stop yourself from witnessing it.   2. You think you know what's going to happen, but once you realize it when the actor does, you're still completely lost for any sort of logical help or saving grace just as they are.   The safe haven of sunlight no longer exists, because Aster has so viciously reminded us that horror can come in all forms, at any time, anywhere.

text: This film was pretty hilarious: SPOILERS!!! Dani's facial expressions, her tripping out, her walking around in those huge pants! Lmao. Will Poulter being in any film should make it a flat comedy, his lines and his delivery were truly funny. Gosh, that orgy scene hahah, Christian being put in a bear and burnt alive...wack, also symbolic, mainly whatever. Yeah, some scenes were disturbing, I mean, most were but the film itself was like a French bizarre-o dark, gross-out comedy. Honestly, it was more similar to Tusk than the Wicker Man (1973 version). Horror it was not. Oddly predictable? Yes. If Wes Anderson directed a horror movie it would still have absurd comedy right? Yeah you'll probably get something similar to this. Still a definite watch for an A24 fan/ lover of all things horror.

Yes there are a few issues with the film such as not doing much when you should kinda know things aren't right, people going missing etc.   Above all else this a film which you cannot unsee. It's better to watch it alone or with someone who takes films serious but be warned... this will make you uncomfortable in ways similar to black mirror but much more intense. text: So, starting off, my name is Dani and the premise reminded me of my boyfriend and his friends, most of whom I've never met or have only had brief encounters with, but still made me feel like it was them who didn't like me. I was thinking "this movie is dumb"--- but having had my fair share of trips, I thought it was at least interesting  enough to watch  to see what their trip was going to be like . Then the movie got weird... & I think the point of the sheer horrid-ness of the film was whether or not the beauty of the surroundings and in the countryside could make up for the corruption within the village; and I think the filmmaker wanted the viewer to ask himself that...... "Do I focus on the beauty of the natural world or the ugliness of humanity?" .  It wasn't a good film, it wasn't a bad film. It was just....a weird film....

People that looked forward to this then watching this and calling it crap - this movie was not supposed to be watched by you, a horror movie for you is The boy or Annabelle, chucky and other movies like that because this is on another level of horror, in this movie it is all about the occult stuff, seeing the sick rituals they do and I can tell y'all  that is definitely NOT how you celebrate midsommar in my country, de don't have pubic hair in pies or human flesh lemonade. This movie is not something you see more than once (unless you are a little bit of a  psychopath), this movie made me sick to my stomach and I couldn't sleep for days. This is not a jump scare movie, I would say this is a movie that is supposed to affect your mental health. So if you are a person that lacks these kinds of emotions to watch a movie like these then...it's just not made for you. When watching this movie...You don't think of it as a movie, it's like you littetally are in it and witnessing the sick stuff they do. text: It took me too long to realize, but this movie actually makes fair sense and is pretty damn good. The whole movie presents the idea that Christian is the "bad boyfriend" or at least someone the audience wouldn't be pleased with. Yet by the end, we see Christian having gone through horrifying experiences of his own almost as if atoning for his negligent attitude towards his role in helping Dani to heal, and even though Dani's presence there was indirectly the reason that all happens to him - even though Christian STILL never had the heart to leave her on her own, he couldn't have been so cruel - Dani makes the shockingly cruel decision to allow him to be taken by the cultists. By doing this, she ends up affording herself the emotional resolve she was in need of. So the movie essentially was about this: Dani cured her emotional trauma, she got Christians help to do so... Christian was mildly cruel to her because his relationship to her caused him mild pain. Dani, at the very end, was extremely cruel to him because her own suffering (part of which from not being supported by Christian well enough) caused her to feel extreme pain.  Dani, the one the audience sympathizes with through the WHOLE movie, is revealed as the true villain. Christian cared about her pain enough not to leave her, although he still could have been more supportive. Dani cared so much about her pain that she kills Christian in order to heal from it when all she had to do was say, "No, don't kill him. He doesn't deserve to die like that."  But she did want him to die, even though he didn't deserve to.  What I like best about this is how it challenges the viewers idea of villainy. The classic take of a villain usually provides a lot of pain and suffering through the villains upbringing and leads them to want to "share their pain" in a twisted act of selfish justice. This is what we see of Dani. She isn't a villain at all, seemingly. She is a poor hurting girl who needs help and support. She has been through cruelty and is feeling misunderstood. All of this works to build up the idea that Dani deserves emotional resolve and Christian is supposed to help her. Think of the following analogy: a parent (Christian) intends to FEED (emotionally support) their kid (Dani) to prevent them from STARVING (committing suicide) but the parent is kinda failing. One day, the parent gets duped, drugged, raped, and paralyzed, meanwhile the kid is at home going hungry. The parent returns home, broken in mind body and spirit, empty handed before the kid. The kid, in need of food and seeing that the parent has failed to perform the duty of feeding them, chooses to have the parent fed to them in order to deal with the hunger...  Yeah, Dani is that bad. She is a maniacally selfish villain by the end of the movie due to the pain of her past. This is an inversion of the traditional method of presenting a villain in the movie to later reveal their tragic backstory which makes you sympathize with them more. Dani's tragedy is revealed immediately and makes us sympathize with her as the victim protagonist... until the very end where we see her evolve into the villain; taking vengeance on Christian to help herself. The bottom line in this: Christian should have left her, but he didn't, he thought that was too cruel. Dani should NOT have killed him, but she did, she didn't think it wasn't fair for her. Christian leaving her probably would have indirectly resulted in her losing her life to suicide, which Christian would have felt extreme pain over. Dani staying with him directly resulted in him being traumatized and killed, which Dani felt no remorse for.   This is the story of how Dani, the protagonist, was formed into the villain through trials of suffering. That's what a "bad guy" is, usually; a hurt person. I think this film really is a masterpiece, but there are some parts to scenes I disagree with. The idea is better than the process of the story.
